{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dowe_ver01/data/sn92073229/00332891868/1958032001/0221.xml":{"full_text":"jiui\nChildress Makes Run For Port\nWhen Crew Member Needs Surgery\nLCDR Howard W. Childress,\nl S. Navy Commander of the\nUSS Thomas J. Gary (DER) and\nformerly a resident of Chapel\nHill, performed a mission of mer\nry on the Atlantic last month.\nWhen a crew member of his\nship was taken ill and required\nsurgical care, LCDR Childress\nimmediately set course for St.\nJohns, Newfoundland, and \u201crang\nup flank speed.\u201d Within 30\nhours from the time the patient\nwas stricken with pain, despite\nDon McKee to Marry Joyce Lilliendahl\nMr. and Mrs. William Lillien\ndahl of Mountain Lakes, N. J.,l\nannounce the approaching mar\nriage of their daughter, Joyce,\nto Donald Kennedy McKee, son\nof William J. McKee, and the\nlate Mrs. McKee, of Chapel Hill.\nThe ceremony will take place\nat tht| bride's home on Saturday,\nMaKR 22, and will be perform\ned by the Rev. Ronald Rowland\nof St. Peter's Episcopal Church.,\nMembers of the immediate fami\nlies will be present. Mrs. Da\nvid Sandeland of Towaco, N. J.,\nwill be the matron of honor, and\nPaul McKee of Annapolis, Mary\nland, will be the best man\nhis brother.\nMiss Lilliendahl was graduated'\nfrom the School of Horticulture\nat Ambler, Pa., and has been a|\nstudent at 'Upsala College, East\nOrange, N. J. For many years\nshe has operated a flower shop\nat Boonton, N. J. Her father is\na nationally known expert on.\nthe rare metal, thorium, and re\ncently received an award* for his\nparticipation in scientific inven-1\ntions which made possible the\natomic energy work of the Man\nX X X \\'N'VN'>A \\'VN'\\ -VV\\'\\'V\\A'N \\'VN->..X'V\nCome into My Harden\nBy Mrs. L. L. Huffman\nX. X X*X*X*X'X*X'X-N*X*X' V*X-V'X\u2018X\u2018X-V'V>X\u2018X>X'X'V'\nThis is the last call for order\ning and planting fruit trees. We\nwho live in cities and villages\nneed not be without fruit any\nmore than our country cousins.\nOur children deserve fresh fruits\nright off the trees. The sooner\nwe plant these trees, the sooner\nour children can enjoy them.\nMy experience with apple\ntrees deserves repeating. 1\nbought, or ordered, one apple\ntree from the first catalogue 1\npicked up ten years ago. Two\nyears ago it bore three apples\u2014\nonly one ripened. Last year it\nbore perhaps a dozen. For in\nformation to my readers 1 advise\nordering from Stark Bros. Nurse\nry, laiuisiana, Mo. Their dwarf\nthe second year after\nplaiw\u00dfig Apples are the same\nsize as -those from standard\ntrees. When three years old,\neach tree will bear more than\na bushel. In fact so many they\nhave to be thinned out before\nripening. There may be other\nreliable nurseries, but I am\nSURE about Starks. It is well\n\u201cALL LS NOT GOLD\nTHAT GUTTERS\"\n(Author\u2019s Name Below)\nRecently our government\nfound it necessary to take\naction against certain door\nto-door salesman of vitamins\nand other medicines. In their\neagerness to make a sale, theae\nagents were making claims\nthat were untrue. Their prices\nwere found to be excessive.\nYour health is too impor\nts to entrust to people of\nno medical or pharmaceutical\nknowledge. Physicians and\npharmacists consider your wel\nfare more important than im\nmediate profits.\nBe safe. IM your physician\nteil you what to take, and\ndepend on us pharmacists to\nmake certain your vitamins\nand medicines are of high\nquality and fairly priced.\n\nASK YOUR PHYSICIAN\nTO PHONE\n9-8781\nWHEN YOU NEED\nA MEDICINE\n\nup jour prescription I\nif shopping near us, or let us\ndeliver promptly without extra\ncharge. A great many people\nentrust us with the responsi\nbility of filling their pre\nscriptions. May we compound\nyours T\nSUTTON\u2019S\nDRUB STORE\nlit B. FraakUe 8t\nPhone 5531 or \u00bb-H7sl\nPRESCRIPTION\nCHEMISTS\n\u2666Quotation by John Heywood\n(1497-1677)\nCopyright 1968 BW4)\nhigh winds and heavy seas, the\nGary was moored at St. Johns.\nThe patient\u2019s surgery was per\nformed and according to the\nlatest reports received by crew\nmembers of the Gary, he is mak\ning a normal recovery. In the\nmeantime the Gary is back at\nsea.\nLCDR Childress and his family\nlived on Dixie Circle in Chapel\nHill for some time before he was\nassigned sea duty about a year\nago. He is a native of Mt. Airy.\nhattan Project. The couple met\ncusr a year ago at Upsala Col-;\nlege, where the groom is an as\nsistant professor of government.!\nDon McKee was educated in\nthe Chapel Hill schools and the\nUniversity here. He worked for\nsix years in the South as rep\nresentative of the Textile Work\ners Union of America (CIO), and\nserved in the U. S. Army in\nFrance, Belgium, and Germany,!\nin World War 11. He received j\nhis Ph.D. degree at Columbia!\nUniversity in 1955, and since\n1960 has taught political science\nat Brooklyn, Hunter, Westmins\nter, and Upsala colleges. He is\nnow also engaged in writing a\nweekly political column in the\nBloomfield Independent Press.\nWhile at the University here\nMr. McKee was editor of the\nDaily Tar Heel, vice-president of.\nthe Y.M.C.A., and a member of.\nPhi Beta Kappa, the Order of:\nthe Grail, and the Golden Fleece.\nHis father has just recently re-!\ntired from the University after\n1 more than 30 years of teaching!\nin the Extension and Education\nDepartments,\nto order early, mid-season, and\nlate trees so that they will be\nripening all summer.\nThey have several varieties of\nJapanese plums which are large,\nfat and juicy. Our one tree\nbears several bushels each year.\nThey are sweet and juicy even\nbefore they art completely ripe\nand we begin eating them long\nbefore the ripened stage. Chil\ndren like the rich sweet flavor\nand here they get plenty of Vita\nmin C.\nAn apricot tree grows well in\nthe Carolinas and because of its\nbeauty in bloom it should be in\nevery garden. It fits well in cor\nners, along the border, or as an\naccent and for shade on the\nlawn. These trees grow into\ncompact form, to about 30 or\nmore feet tall and bear well for\nthirty years or more. Blooms\n1 are a delicate pink, resembling\n1 those of the crab, making it ex\ncellent for landscape purposes.\nMy tree, planted last fall, seems\nto have withstood all our hard\n1 freezing weather and is about\nready to burst out in leaf.\nThere is no fruit more delici\nous than the Japanese persim-\nRevival Is Planned\nBy Ephesus Church\nThe Ephesus Baptist Church\non Pope Road, betweea Highway\n54 to Raleigh and Highway 16-\n601 to Durham, is making ex\ntensive plans for an Easter re\nvival crusade. Services will he\nheld at 7;30 p.m. daily from Ap\nril 6 through April 13. The Rev.\nU. A. McManus Jr. of Warsaw\nwill be the evangelist. The Rev.\nM. Kenneth Wilson, pastor of\nthe church, will direct the revival\nmusic.\nLacy Thomas, superintendent\nof the Sunday School, and B. W.\nClark, associate superintendent\nof the Sunday school, are con\nducting a program of visitation.\nThey plan a special attendance\ndrive during the week of the\nmeeting. Home prayer meetings\nwill be held during the week pre\nceding the services.\nEverybody is invited to take\npart in this evangelistic crusade.\nOfficers Elected\nBy P.E.O. Chapter\nMrs. William R. Straughn of\n10b Hillsboro Street ia the new\npresident of P.E.O. Sorority,\nChapter F, composed of Chapel\nHill and Durham resident*.\nAlso installed after the elec\ntion at a meeting at the home\nof the Misses Lilly and Mary\nRobinson, 2729 Circle Drive, Dur\nham, were Mrs. John W. Lesley\nJr., 623 Rosemary Street, chap\nlain, and the following from Dur\nham: Mrs. John N. Macduff,\nvice-president; Mrs. Burley H.\nMcGraw, recording secretary;\nMrs. Herman Salinger, corre\nsponding secretary; Mrs. T. W.\nMinah, treasurer, and Miss Ma\nry Robinson, guard.\nMrs. Joel Carter of 601 Laurel\nHill Road is the retiring presi\ndent.\ntnon, which in si*e and color re\nsembles an orange\u2014large, fat,\nseedless, and juicy. Flavor is\nbetween an old fashioned persim\nmon and a banana. For a break\nfast treat, for lunch or dinner\u2014\nor just to pick and eat right\nfrom the tree they are delicious,\nand ripen in September. This is\nmy first year to give it a trial\nand 1 can hardly wait for fruit.\nLet\u2019s make our homes homey\nwith fruits, nut trees and berries.\nDon\u2019t omit blueberries.\nNORTH CAROLINA\nORANGE COUNTY\nADMINISTRATOR\u2019S NOTICE\nThe undersigned, having qual\nified as administrator of the\nestate of William E. Parrish, de\nceased, late of Orange County,\nthis is to notify all persons hav-,\n;ing claims against said estate to\npresent them to the undersigned\non or before the 6th day of\nMarch, 1959, or this notice will\nbe pleaded in bar of their re\ncovery. All persons indebted to\nsaid estate will please make im\nmediate payment to the under\nsigned.\nThis the 4th day of March,\n1968.\nJames E. Parrish, Administrator\nof the estate of William E. Par\nrish, deceased, R.F.D. 1, Durham,\nIn. c.\nJames R. Farlow, Attorney\nChapel Hill, North Carolina\nj t\nWaiter JSonneli i] \u2022Sucti.'O/ieMet\nnianj tolors, now shaping up for Easier parading\nStraws v-* suits and coats! Choose from a variety that I\nV was never bigjfer or better exciting new\nHead the K* V k Silhouettes to flatter every figure, rich fabrics,\nAccessories Or Complete Ensembles\nCompetent Clerks Courteous Service Free\nGuaranteed Quality Price Parking\nNORTH CAROLINA\nORANGE COUNTY\nADMINISTRATOR\u2019S NOTICE\nThe undersigned, having qual\nified as administrator of the\nestate of Lila B. Parrish, de\nceased, late of Orange County,\nthis is to notify all persons hav\ning claims against said estate to\npresent them to the undersigned\non or before the 6th day of\nMarch, 1959, or this notice willl\nbe pleaded in bar of their re-|\neovery. All persons indebted to\nsaid estate will please make im\nmediate payment to the under- j\nsigned.\nThis the 4th day of March,\n1958.\nJames E. Parrish, Administrator\nof the estate of Lila B. Parrish,\ndeceased; R.F.D. 1, Durham, N.\n;c.\nJames R. Farlow, Attorney\nChapel Hill, North Carolina\n\nNORTH CAROLINA\nORANGE COUNTY\nNOTICE\nThe undersigned, having quali\nfied as executrix of the estate\nof James S. Tippett, deceased,\nlate of Orange County, this is\nto notify all persons having\nclaims against said estate to\npresent them to the undersigned\non or before the 27th day of\nFebruary, 1959, or this notice\nwill be pleaded in bar of their\nrecovery. All persons indebted\nto said estate will please make\nimmediate payment to the under\nsigned.\nThis the 27th day of February,\n1958.\nMartha Kelly Tippett\nExecutrix\nJohn W. Lasley, Attorney\nBrockwell Building\nNOTICE OF SALE\nUnder and by virtue of the\npower conferred upon me in a\ncertain deed of trust executed to\nme by Raymond Riggsbee and\nwife, Eva Mae Riggsbee, dated\nDecember 6, 1951, and recorded\nin the Office of the Register of\nDeeds of Orange County in Book\n114, at page 390, to secure the\nindebtedness therein described,\nand default having been made in\nthe payment of said indebted\nnes, and having been requested;\nto do so by the holder of the!\nnote evidencing said indebted\nness, 1 will offer for sale at pub\nlic auction to the highest bidder\nfor cash at the Post Office Door\nm Clmpel Hill, North Carolina,\nat 12 o\u2019clock Noon, on\nFRIDAY, MARCH 28, 1958\nthe following described land, to\nwit:\nAll that certain tract or parcel\nof land situated, lying and being\non the South side of Carr Street\nin the Town of Carrboro, N. C.,\nand more particularly described 1\nI as BEGINNING at an iron stake\nin the South property line of the\nsaid Street, the Northeast corner\nof the property of Nannie Riggs\nbee; running thence along the\nSouth property line of the said\nStreet North 85\u201d East 76 feet to\nan iron stake, Lola C. Riggsbee s\ncorner; running thence with the\nsaid Riggsbee\u2019s line South 2\u201d\nWest 186.8 feet to an iron stake;\nrunning thence with Nannie\nRiggsbee\u2019s line North 85* West\n49 feet to an iron stake and\nNorth 7* West 173 feet to the\nBEGINNING.\nThis sale will be held open for\nten days to receive increased\nbids.\nThis the 21st day of February,\n1958.\nL. J. Phipps\nTRUSTEE\nj ADMINISTRATRIX\u2019 NOTICE\nHaving qualified as Adminis\ntratrix of the estate of Pauliue\nLloyd, deceased, late of Orange\nCounty, North Carolina, I here\njby notify all persons having\n.claims against the estate of said\ndeceased to exhibit them to the\nundersigned on Route 2, Chapel\nHill, on or before the 13th day\nof February, 1969, or this notice\nwill be pleaded in bar of their\nrecovery. All persons indebted\nto said estate will please make\nimmediate payment\n1 This the 14th day of Febru\nary, 1958.\nRuby L. Layton, Administra\ntrix of the estate of Pauline\n\u2022j Lloyd, deceased.\nii\nNOTICE OF SALE\n1 Under and by virtue of the\npower conferred upon me in a\ncertain deed of trust executed\nto me by Bobby R. Roberts and\nwife. Ruby Miller Roberts, dat\ned December 9, 1965, and record\ned in the Office of the Register\nof Deeds of Orange County in\nBook 135, at page 127, to secure\nthe indebtedness therein describ- i\ned, and default having been made!\nin the payment of said indebted-l\nness, and having been requested)\nto do so by th c holder of the\nnote evidencing said indebted\nness, I will offer for sale at pub\nlic auction to the highest bidder\nfor cash at the Post Office Door\nin Chapel Hill, North Carolina,\nat 12:20 o\u2019clock P. M., on\nTUESDAY, MARCH 25, 1968\ni the following described land, to\ni wit:\nAll that certain lot or parcel\nof land situated, lying and being\nat the Northwestern intersection\n1 of Alabama Avenue and Neville\nDrive and known and designated\naa Lot No. 2 of the Subdivision\nof Tract K 5 of the I. S. WEAV\nER PROPERTY and known as\nthence along the West property\nmore particularly described as\nBEGINNNING at a stake in the\nsaid intersection and running\nj line of Alabama Avenua North\n-4\u201d 21\u2019 West 50 feet to a stake,\nthe Southeast corner of Lot No.\n1; running thenee with the line\nof the said lot South 86* 49'\nWest 139.57 feet to a stake;\nrunning thenee South 4* 51\u2019\ni East 50 feet to a stake in the\nI North property line of Neville\nDrive; running thence along the\nNorth property line of the said\nDrive North 86* 49\u2019 East 139.13\n;feet to the BEGINNING.\nThis sale will be held open\nfor ten days to receive increased\ni bids.\nThis the 18th day of February,\n11968.\nL. J. Phipps\nTRUSTEE\nADMINISTRATOR\u2019S NOTICE\nThe undersigned, having qual\nified as administrator of the\nEstate of Robert Chester Hin\nnant, deceased, late of Orange\nCounty, this is to notify all par\nsons having chums against said\nestate to present tXam to the\nundersigned on or before the 13th\nday of March, 1963, or this notice\nwill be pleaded in bar of their\nrecovery. AH persons Indebted\nto said estate will pleaae make\npayment te the undersigned.\nThis the 13th day of March,\n1968.\nL. J. Phipps, Administrator of\nthe Estate es Robert Chester\nH inn ant","height":"26470","width":"19978"}}
